        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 26:38-41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; the present passage; and ch. 8. Our present passage mentions three sons, as though they were all, and immediately proceeds to their posterity. The list in Genesis mentions ten, of whom, however, we know (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 26:40",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 8:3, 4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") that three, Naaman, Ard, and Gem, were grandsons, being sons of Bela, under which circumstances the order in which the two former stand in Genesis is remarkable. Again, while Becher is given as the second son in both Genesis and our present place, he is not mentioned in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 26:38-41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 8:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Ashbel, who in Genesis is given as the third, is expressly called the second son. Among the Ephraimites, however (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 26:35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), a Becher, with his descendants the Bachrites, is mentioned, and it is not improbable that, by marriage, the family were at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "that time",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", for manifest reasons of inheritance and possession, reckoned in this tribe, though by blood of the tribe of Benjamin. This subject is skilfully discussed by Lord A. C. Hervey (Smith's 'Bible Dictionary,' 1:175). Lastly, Jediael of this passage and ver. 10 is not found in Genesis, in Numbers, or in our ch. 8. This name seems to have superseded in our passage the name Ashbel in Genesis, though it is impossible to speak certainly. It cannot be supposed to designate the same person, but rather a descendant in the same branch, whose family had come to importance \"in the days of David.\" 1 Chronicles 7:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Sons and families of Benjamin. - In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 7:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " only three sons of Benjamin-Bela, Becher, and Jediael - are mentioned; and in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 7:7-11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " their families are registered. Besides these, there are five sons of Benjamin spoken of in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 8:1-2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", - Bela the first, Ashbel the second, Aharah the third, Nohah the fourth, and Rapha the fifth; while in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 7:3-5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " five other בּנים are enumerated, viz., אדּר, גּרא (twice), נעמן, שׁפוּפן, and חוּרם. If we compare here the statements of the Pentateuch as to the genealogy of Benjamin, we find in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 46:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the following sons of Benjamin: Bela, Becher, Ashbel, Gera, Naaman, Ehi (אחי) and Rosh, Muppim and Huppim and Ard (ארדּ); and in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 26:38-40",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " seven families, of which five are descended from his sons Bela, Ashbel, Ahiram, Shephupham, and Hupham (חוּפם); and two from his grandsons, the sons of Bela, Ard and Naaman. From this we learn, not only that of the בּנים mentioned in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 46:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " at least two were grandsons, but also that the names אחי and מפּים (Gen.) are only other forms of אחירם and שׁפוּפם (Num.). It is, however, somewhat strange that among the families (in Num.) the names בּכר, גּרא, and ראשׁ are wanting. The explanation which at once suggests itself, that their descendants were not numerous enough to form separate families, and that they on that account were received into the families of the other sons, though it may be accepted in the case of Gera and Rosh, of whom it is nowhere recorded that they had numerous descendants, cannot meet the case of Becher, for in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 7:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 7:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of our chapter mention is made of nine sons of his, with a posterity of 20,200 men. The supposition that the name of Becher and his family has been dropped from the genealogical register of the families in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", will not appear in the slightest degree probable, when we consider the accuracy of this register in other respects. The only remaining explanation therefore is, that the descendants of Becher were in reality not numerous enough to form a משׁפּחה by themselves, but had afterwards so increased that they numbered nine fathers'-houses, with a total of 20,200 valiant warriors. The numbers in our register point unquestionably to post-Mosaic times; for at the second numbering by Moses, all the families of Benjamin together numbered only 45,600 men (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 26:41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), while the three families mentioned in our verses number together 59,434 (22,034 + 20,200 + 17,200). The tribe of Benjamin, which moreover was entirely destroyed, with the exception of 600 men, in the war which it waged against the other tribes in the earlier part of the period of the judges (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 20:47",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), could not have increased to such an extent before the times of David and Solomon. The name of the third son of Benjamin, Jediael, occurs only here, and is considered by the older commentators to be another name of Ashbel (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 46:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 26:38",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), which cannot indeed be accepted as a certainty, but is very probable.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]